        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(trust): sanitize set:html in localized trust pages to prevent XSS",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThe localized trust pages (ja, ko, zh-cn) render i18n JSON strings via Astro `set:html` without sanitization. All 39 `set:html` usages pass translation strings directly as raw HTML. If a malicious translation string were introduced through a contributed PR, it could inject arbitrary HTML/JS into the built site.\n\nThis is the same class of vulnerability fixed in #140 (YAML data escaping) and #142 (author name encoding), now applied to the i18n trust page content.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `src/lib/sanitize-html.ts` (NEW): `sanitizeTrustHtml` utility that strips all tags except a safe allowlist (`strong`, `em`, `b`, `i`, `code`, `br`, `a` with https href, `span` with class, `sup`, `sub`, `ul`, `ol`, `li`). Unsafe tags are HTML-escaped; `a` href values must start with `https://`.\n- `src/pages/trust/ja/index.astro`: Wrap all 13 `set:html` usages with sanitizer (imported as `s`)\n- `src/pages/trust/zh-cn/index.astro`: Wrap all 10 `set:html` usages with sanitizer (imported as `s`)\n- `src/pages/trust/ko/index.astro`: Wrap all 16 `set:html` usages with sanitizer (imported as `san` to avoid conflict with existing `s` loop variable)\n\n## Verification\n\nBehavior addressed: Unsanitized set:html in localized trust pages allows HTML/JS injection via translation JSON\nReal environment tested: macOS, local Astro build\nExact steps or command run after this patch: `npx astro build`\nEvidence after fix: All 22 pages build successfully with zero errors\nObserved result after fix: All set:html values pass through sanitizeTrustHtml before rendering; `<script>`, `<img onerror>`, and other dangerous tags would be HTML-escaped while safe formatting tags (`<strong>`, `<code>`, `<a href=\"https://...\">`) pass through\nWhat was not tested: Visual rendering of all 3 localized trust pages in a browser (build success confirms no Astro compilation errors)\n",
